And he also turned his back when he could have easily prevented the Sabra and Chatila massacres.  He was even found culpable by an Israeli board of judicial inquiry if I'm not mistaken.  There are few angels on either side currently, not many that I'd willingly trust at any rate.  As far as people strapping bombs to themselves go- I agree it can't be condoned- but nor can putting a bullet in the head of a teenage boy throwing a stone.  Be honest with me Cus- in your experience &amp; knowledge, how many times have you witnessed a fatality involving a teenage boy throwing a rock?  Or even a serious injury?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What Israel is doing to protect itself is nothing different than what America is doing in Afghanistan, only that instead of the terrorists being 13000 miles away, In Israel they are sometimes a few city blocks from their targets.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I understand where you're coming from Cus, but with all due respect- the US didn't bomb Afghanistan <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>indiscriminately</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Whereas I would argue Sharon's bulldozers ploughing down entire residential areas is both confrontational and indiscriminate.  And it's not suprising there is anger and confusion when Israeli settlements(effectively squatters on Palestinian land) are encouraged to settle in those areas, while Palestinian homes are bulldozed.  If you're looking for a terrorist in a 5 block radius- Sharon's solution seems to be to destroy every dwelling within that radius.<br>
<br>
The Israeli government is also one of the very few to openly admit torturing its victims physically, as well as imprisoning several individuals without trial.  Whether that's necessary or not is arguable- the fact that these measures are inhumane is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>not</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> arguable Cus.<br>
<br>
I'm not taking sides here either- the PA in its current form is as corrupt as can be.  In fact, I would surmise that the most recent attack is aimed as much at the PA's current attempts to reform as it is towards the Israeli government.  Such institutional reform is critical if the PA is ever to be taken seriously.  However, that institutional reform can only take place in an environment of trust.  Only be engaging with each others' demands, and with full cooperation of the parties will that be achieved.  <br>
<br>
The solution is one most everybody agrees on- withdrawal to pre-1967 borders, the creation of a Palestinian state etc- the Roadmap and the details though, are sketchy.  I for one, don't think any further settlement can be achieved with the current leadership of either side.  You can argue Sharon is doing what he needs to do to surivive politically Cus, but history doesn't view that attitude kindly.  Barak and Rabin, *especially* Yitzhak Rabin will go down in history as men who made sacrifices for peace- the latter sacrificed his life for it and will be remembered alongside Sadat (who incidentally met his end at the hands of a PLO gunman in one of Yasser Arafat's crack death squads.  Note also- that both were shot by their own people- Rabin was shot by a jewish Zionist- and Sadat by a PLO extremist..  Extremism in all its forms has a dirty way of expressing itself- and both sides have their fair share.  The current leaders are incapable of controlling factions within their respective movements- an internationally regulated referendum for each candidate from either side (for the sake of equality) might be an idea to break the political deadlock and rub some credibility off on the Palestinian Authority (hopefully by that time reformed to some extent).<br>
<br>
Now the only realistic solution in my mind is to stop the settlements, and make a clear statement about what land will <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>eventually</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> form a Palestinian state.  After reform of the PA and an environment having been built between two ambitious leaders committed to peace- we will be ready to start walking the roadmap.  But for that road to be even and untroubled- the US &amp; UK must cease their unilateral support of Israel- rather, support both sides.  Don't cut Israels' 2 bln of aid- but give the Palestinians an equal share of the money, their fair share of the land- and autonomy (when they're ready for it).  <br>
<br>
Israel is no longer surrounded by enemies in the same way it was 30-40 years ago.  There is a very strong case for peace and for bold decisions to be made on both sides.  If someone doesn't step up to the crease soon, I vrey much fear the extremists on both sides will be the only winners.<br>
<br>
